column169: On April 3, 2024, one (1) 55-gallon drum of UN3098 was damaged prior to arrival and released approximately 55-gallons of product to the trailer interior and further migrated to the asphalt. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Thin Line Environmental (TLE) to remediate the impacted site. Crews collected the damaged 55-gallon drum and placed it in a 95-gallon over-pack drum for disposal. TLE deployed soda ash to the impacted asphalt and trailer floor to neutralize the release. Crews utilized hand tools to collect all impacted soda ash from the asphalt and the trailer floor. All hydrogen peroxide and peroxyacetic acid impacted material was collected and containerized in one (1) 95-gallon drum and thirteen (13) 35-gallon drums and added to RLC waste stream for disposal.

column169: Mechanical employee conducting an outbound inspection noticed the strong smell of sulfur in the area of SHPX 209817.  He left the area and reported it.  NS Haz Mat and contractor responded checked the car and found high S02 reading around the manway area.  We could also hear a hissing from the manway.  Tightening manway bolts did not stop leak.  Manway was opened and found to have two (2) gaskets in place, one flat in the manway cover and one mounted on the manway nozzle.  Both gaskets were removed and replaced with new one.  Manway was secured and tested with meter.  No detect.  Car was release for transportation.

Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 55-gallons of product released to a 36’ x 24’ area of the concrete dock floor due to a forklift puncture. The damaged drum was placed into an 85-gallon metal overpack. Absorbents were then worked into the impacted area. The impacted absorbents were collected into (4) 55-gallon metal drums. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column169: XPO Logistics terminal NCH experienced a UN1824 Greasestrip Plus release from a box containing (4) 1-gallon poly jugs as well as a release of UN3264 Lime-A-Way from a box containing (4) 1-gallon poly jugs. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 2-gallons of each product, (4-gallons combined) released to a 4’ x 4’ area of the trailer floor due to a forklift puncture. Soda ash solution and oil dri were deployed to clean and neutralize the impacted area. All impacted absorbents, cardboard, PPE, and the two empty pails of UN3264 Lime-A-Way were placed into a 55-gallon poly drum. The two empty jugs, and two damaged jugs of UN1824 Greasestrip Plus were placed into a separate 55-gallon poly drum. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.
